Correlation with Heatmap¶

A correlation heatmap uses colored cells, typically in a monochromatic scale, to show a 2D correlation matrix (table) between two discrete dimensions or event types. It is very important in Feature Selection

In [20]:
# we have to create a model such that we are able to predict the tip based on other parameters.
# tip is dependent feature.
# total bill, sex, smoker,day,time,size all this is independent feature.

# heatmap help to analyse the colrelation between all the features -> can be found out only if they are int or float.
# if values are categarial feature it is not possible as it is categaru type.
# value range byw -1 to 1 . coeff corealation.
In [ ]:
## It is very important in process of feature selection.
In [38]:
numeric_df = df.select_dtypes(include=['float64', 'int64'])
correlation_matrix = numeric_df.corr()
print(correlation_matrix)

            total_bill       tip      size
total_bill    1.000000  0.675734  0.598315
tip           0.675734  1.000000  0.489299
size          0.598315  0.489299  1.000000
In [50]:
sns.heatmap(correlation_matrix)
Out[50]:
<Axes: >

1 JoinPlot¶

  • A join plot allows to study the relationship between 2 numeric variables.
  • The central chart display their correlation.
  • It is usually a scatterplot, a hexbin plot, a 2D histogram or a 2D density plot

Bivariate Analysis:¶

In [55]:

2: Pair plot¶

  • A “pairs plot” is also known as a scatterplot, in which one variable in the same data row is matched with another variable's value, like this: Pairs plots are just elaborations on this, showing all variables paired with all the other variables

Categorical plot¶

Seaborn also helps us in doing the analysis on Categorical Data points. In this section we will discuss about

  • box plot
  • violinplot
  • countplot
  • bar plot

1 Count plot¶

In [90]:

<Axes: xlabel='sex', ylabel='count'>
